# Methods âš™ï¸

Objects can also have methods. Methods are actions that can be performed on objects.

Methods are stored in properties as function definitions.

```javascript
const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  fullName: function() {
    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
  }
};

console.log(person.fullName());
```
- `this` refers to the owner of the function (the person object).

# Iterating Arrays ðŸ”„

Modern ways to loop.

## forEach()
Calls a function once for each array element.

```javascript
const numbers = [45, 4, 9];
numbers.forEach(myFunction);

function myFunction(value, index, array) {
  console.log(value);
}
```

## map()
Creates a new array by performing a function on each array element.
```javascript
const numbers1 = [45, 4, 9];
const numbers2 = numbers1.map(value => value * 2);
```

# Filter & Reduce ðŸ”

## filter()
Creates a new array with array elements that pass a test.
```javascript
const ages = [32, 33, 16, 40];
const adults = ages.filter(age => age >= 18);
```

## reduce()
Runs a function on each array element to produce (reduce it to) a single value.
```javascript
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const sum = numbers.reduce((total, value) => total + value);
```

# Destructuring Objects ðŸ“¦

Unpack properties from objects into distinct variables.

```javascript
const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  age: 50
};

// Old way
// let firstName = person.firstName;

// Destructuring
const { firstName, age } = person;
console.log(firstName); // John
```

# Spread Operator ... ðŸ§ˆ

Expands an iterable (like an array) into more elements.

```javascript
const q1 = ["Jan", "Feb", "Mar"];
const q2 = ["Apr", "May", "Jun"];
const halfYear = [...q1, ...q2];
```

Also works for Objects (cloning/merging):
```javascript
const obj1 = { foo: 'bar', x: 42 };
const obj2 = { foo: 'baz', y: 13 };
const mergedObj = { ...obj1, ...obj2 };
```

